feeling:
When it's about topics I am passionate about, I enjoy writing about them because I am (most of the time) confident in how I want to integrate my voice into my output. I have often already have my own opinions about the topic that I want to further expound on with more research. 

That said, writing longer papers is a lot more tedious for me and I feel more at ease when coming up with something like a feature article or a speech.
will_affect:
Feedback from people who have more experience with writing helps a lot. Their edits and comments help me realize what tone should I use for a particular type of written output and what I should highlight to readers. Also, feedback helps me identify how to further strengthen my arguments for future work. 

Lastly, I think confidence in writing can be improved with regular practice and application of what I've learned. Different types of written outputs require different structure and tone.  Writing academic and research papers are more of a challenge to me compared to news and feature articles (I have more experience with the latter). With that, I think that confidence in writing comes along with more experience and practice, with the help of feedback so you actually get someone else's perspective on how to improve.

feeling:
Writing is okay. I recognize its necessity for many processes, like working on projects, mass communicating relevant results, day-to-day activities, ensuring efficiency and accuracy of systems and outputs, and others.

I am interested in writing only because it is very important for day-to-day communication, academic pursuits, and business matters. Overall, it is absolutely necessary when discussing, documenting, and working on thoughts and ideas - and so I like writing. 

However, I am not really interested in writing creatively. For me, writing is a means, not a passionate pursuit in itself. For example, I like sharing thoughts and ideas and discussing with others - writing happens to be an important part of this endeavor. Thus, writing in itself is not a "passion" but it is subsumed in (i.e., part and parcel of) some of my passions - and so I enjoy writing mainly only to the extent that I enjoy the parent endeavor (like discussing and articulating thoughts for sharing, improvement, and documentation). 

In statistical terms, the zero-order interest I have in writing is high. However, when other variables are controlled for, the marginal interest I have in writing is low.

I guess you could say that I like writing because of its utility, not its potential for artistic stuff. This, of course, does not mean that I do not enjoy reading creative pieces. It's just that I myself am not interested in producing such creative pieces.
will_affect:
I am moderately confident in writing. Intuitively, learning more about or reviewing grammar, learning more about writing principles, and expanding vocabulary are good ways to improve confidence in writing. 

As for specific processes or ways to gain confidence in writing, I generally find having others critique my writing a good way for me to understand more about how recipient(s) will take the material (and consequently, improve my confidence in writing).
